When $\mathrm{IRR}$ is greater than the required return $(\mathrm{IRR}>i)$ then the project should be accepted, and;

When the $\mathrm{IRR}$ is less than the required return $(\mathrm{IRR}<i)$ then the project should be rejected.

Now, what we are seeing in formula $(1)$ is that $\mathrm{IRR}$ makes the $\mathrm{NPV}$ of all cash flows equal to zero in a discounted cash flow analysis.
